            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nWe recommend studying the previous text (<htcite0>) and its prerequisites, to better understand this game.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e92e3d06-886e-4d3c-811f-bcbcce9aa832",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Change of Direction",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen we look at the numbers used in the Andes or in Mesoamerica, both regions of the American continent (*Abya Yala*), we observe that the numbers were written vertically, and not horizontally, as we do today (<htcite0>).\n\nThis fact leads us to a reflection:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e92e3d06-886e-4d3c-811f-bcbcce9aa832",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Change of Direction",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: The Inverse</b><br /><br />Would you know how to say which was the first being to walk on two feet, as we do today?<br /><br />When answering the first question, did you think only of us? Or did you think of other species?<br /><br />The fact that indigenous peoples wrote their numbers vertically, could it be related to the way we walk?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_erectus",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### The first one to walk was...\n\nBefore we understood the existence of fossils, genetics, and other knowledge acquired only in the last few centuries, the answer to who was the first to walk depended on the region of the world, according to people's conclusions. However, thanks to advances in knowledge, the scenario has changed, and today we can better express which was the first animal to walk on two feet as we currently do (<htcite0>).\n\nThe first animal to walk on two feet like us was also of the genus *Homo*, but it was not a *Homo sapiens* like us. That first living being is known as *Homo erectus* (**Figura 1**), and the first fossil was found in <htdate0> in Indonesia, being dated to around <htdate1> (<htcite1>; <htcite2>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ab1dda1e-95c2-4087-8299-e851e58bdc6f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Humans",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7fa66cfd-dca8-4a17-bead-e79954ba684a",
                     "text": "Wood, B., & Collard, M.",
                     "page": "pp. 65",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1999",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "4a3de4c9-f79d-4426-a447-e1272ff3a6f7",
                     "text": "Dorey, Fran",
                     "page": "Homo erectus",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "10",
                        "day": "16"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1890",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "-1900000",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/DonsMaps/img_6776erectusdmanisi.jpg\" id=\"imgHe\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHe', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\" style=\"width: 40%;\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Skull of <i>Homo erectus</i> on the left. © Don Hitchcock. Original at the <i>Vienna Natural History Museum</i> (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e9309ef1-64dc-4e30-8991-2d4e1c7dd055",
                     "text": "Hitchcock, Don",
                     "page": "Homo erectus",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2015",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The fact that the fossil — in the case of humans, the bones of a deceased human — was found in Asia ended up generating several questions, as the origin of the genus *Homo* occurred in Africa. With further studies, it was possible to find new fossils in Africa, which allowed a better understanding of the evolution of species within the genus *Homo* (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nIn **Figure 2**, we present another fossil, known as **Homo ergaster*, which, despite sharing characteristics with *Homo erectus*, does not have exactly the same ones, which is why it is considered a different species (<htcite2>). In addition to this new fossil, we also placed a poster with a skeleton like ours side by side, so we can reflect further.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "75d196c9-1c1e-4106-bef5-ce8558d00d31",
                     "text": "Tattersall, I., & Schwartz, J. H.",
                     "page": "pp. 74 - 75",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ab1dda1e-95c2-4087-8299-e851e58bdc6f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Humans",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "75d196c9-1c1e-4106-bef5-ce8558d00d31",
                     "text": "Tattersall, I., & Schwartz, J. H.",
                     "page": "pp. 73",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"book_navigation\"><tr><td><i>Homo ergaster</i></td><td><i>Homo sapiens</i></td></tr><tr><td><img id=\"imgHer\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHer', '0%')\" src=\"images/DonsMaps/1594.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" style=\"width: 25%\"/></td><td><img id=\"imgHs3\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHs3', '0%')\" src=\"images/MexicoCityMuseo/HomoSapiens.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%;\"/></td></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 2</b>: Fossil of <i>Homo ergaster</i> on the left. © Don Hitchcock. Original at the <i>Western Australian Museum</i> (<htcite0>). Poster of the human skeleton describing <i>Homo sapiens</i> on the right. At the Museu Nacional de Antrologia no México (<htcite1>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "816d0d03-bd90-4bcd-84ef-a2316dc68eff",
                     "text": "Hitchcock, Don",
                     "page": "Homo erectus - Homo ergaster",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2013",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0be2ea18-ab78-4cb1-b3be-1ff0ba4ade95",
                     "text": "Museo Nacional de Antropologia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Our family?</b><br /><br />In this text, we talk about <i>Homo erectus</i>, <i>Homo ergaster</i>, and us, <i>Homo sapiens</i>. How are we and the other species connected?<br /><br />If DNA — the part of living beings' bodies responsible for transmitting characteristics — did not have the ability to change over time, we would not exist. As fortunately these changes exist and are small from one generation to the next, we can imagine something: suppose a change that allowed us to walk on two feet had never occurred. Do you think we would occupy all places on the planet as we do today?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Since, in this text, our objective is to present that we were neither the only nor the first animals to walk on the face of the Earth, we will not go into the details presented in the text about humans (<htcite0>). Even so, we extract from that text a graph that shows our relationship with these and other species (<htcite1>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ab1dda1e-95c2-4087-8299-e851e58bdc6f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Humans",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7fa66cfd-dca8-4a17-bead-e79954ba684a",
                     "text": "Wood, B., & Collard, M.",
                     "page": "pp. 68",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1999",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p id=\"circtri0\"><div class=\"atlasCircleContainer\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 600 340\" class=\"circle-draw\" id=\"svgcirctri0\">  <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"3\" markerHeight=\"3\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <text x=\"42\" y=\"60\" font-size=\"0.6em\" font-style=\"italic\" transform=\"rotate(-35, 70, 60)\">Paranthropus africanus</text> <text x=\"72\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"0.6em\" font-style=\"italic\" transform=\"rotate(-35, 70, 60)\">Australopithecus africanus</text> <text x=\"112\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"0.6em\" font-style=\"italic\" transform=\"rotate(-35, 110, 60)\">Paranthropus aethiopicus</text> <text x=\"152\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"0.6em\" font-style=\"italic\" transform=\"rotate(-35, 150, 60)\">Paranthropus boisei</text> <text x=\"192\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"0.6em\" font-style=\"italic\" transform=\"rotate(-35, 190, 60)\">Paranthropus robustus</text> <text x=\"232\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"0.6em\" font-style=\"italic\" transform=\"rotate(-35, 230, 60)\">Homo habilis</text> <text x=\"272\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"0.6em\" font-style=\"italic\" transform=\"rotate(-35, 270, 60)\">Homo rudolfensis</text> <text x=\"312\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"0.6em\" font-style=\"italic\" transform=\"rotate(-35, 310, 60)\">Homo ergaster</text> <text x=\"352\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"0.6em\" font-style=\"italic\" transform=\"rotate(-35, 350, 60)\">Homo erectus</text> <text x=\"392\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"0.6em\" font-style=\"italic\" transform=\"rotate(-35, 390, 60)\">Homo heidelbergensis</text> <text x=\"432\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"0.6em\" font-style=\"italic\" transform=\"rotate(-35, 430, 60)\">Homo neanderthalensis</text> <text x=\"472\" y=\"75\" font-size=\"0.6em\" font-style=\"italic\" transform=\"rotate(-35, 470, 60)\">Homo sapiens</text> <line x1=\"220\" y1=\"324\" x2=\"475\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"253\" y1=\"294\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"273\" y1=\"274\" x2=\"84\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"295\" y1=\"254\" x2=\"126\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"164\" y1=\"119\" x2=\"197\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"164\" y1=\"119\" x2=\"164\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"295\" y1=\"254\" x2=\"242\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"295\" y1=\"254\" x2=\"282\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"397\" y1=\"156\" x2=\"326\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"397\" y1=\"156\" x2=\"366\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"397\" y1=\"156\" x2=\"404\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"397\" y1=\"156\" x2=\"444\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"black\" /></svg></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 2</b>: Phylogenetic relationship of hominids.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Notice, in **Graph 2**, that our species is the last one on the right side, which does not mean anything special, like being better or superior. This graph shows how the species are related. Through it, we see that *Homo ergaster* is closer to *Homo erectus*, while species like *Homo neandertalensis*, and *Homo heidelbergensis* are closer to us.\n\nFurthermore, we see that, in the distant past, we all had common ancestors, which is why we share several characteristics.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_music",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Music\n\nAlthough we cannot affirm that Mesoamerican numbers are related to feet, this is a common practice, given the fact that they are vigesimal numbers (<htcite0>).\n\nIf we cannot affirm that feet were used to create a new numerical system, it is possible to say that, using feet and hands, we have developed exercises and dances that keep us healthy and help us learn, as can be seen in different videos on social media (<htcite1>).\n\nIn this text, we propose one more game in which we use feet and hands to learn indigenous numbers.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "34560ef7-523d-4b51-9264-b3b0288213a0",
                     "text": "Justeson, J. S.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 3,
                     "uuid": "be9c8b1b-8708-4173-8ee4-e60efd20a179",
                     "text": "Henri Gaobi - Master Drummer",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_game",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### The game\n\nWhen we clap our hands or stomp our feet, we generate a sound. This sound depends on the speed at which we clap our hands, walk, or jump. Furthermore, we can combine claps and steps, creating rhythms and music.\n\nIn this text, we will again use our bodies in learning. Next, choose the number of times the hands will clap, or the number of steps or jumps. Then, choose the speed and a color for the body parts. **Note that, regardless of the chosen color, the movements will be the same, because we are all equal, regardless of our color** (<htcite0>; <htcite1>). We are all equal because we emerged in Africa around 300,000 years ago (<htcite2>). The different skin colors occur, basically, due to the amount of melanin that populations have and the environment in which they live, with darker skins being predominant in regions close to the Equator — an imaginary line that divides the Earth in half — and lighter skins in more distant regions (<htcite3>).\n\nFinally, press clap (<i class=\"fa-solid fa-hands-clapping\" onclick=\"startClap()\" style=\"font-size:1em;color:#0f0;\" ></i>), walk (<i class=\"fa-solid fa-person-walking\" onclick=\"startSteps()\" style=\"font-size:1em;color:#f00;\" ></i>), and jump (<i class=\"fa-solid fa-person-running\" onclick=\"startJump()\" style=\"font-size:1em;color:#00f;\" ></i>). Perform the movements along with the app.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2659babf-36dc-480f-a3d9-d37b8c4e1159",
                     "text": "Templeton A. R.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2013",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "723b0735-b8c4-4b02-8ce6-6da033ca2454",
                     "text": "Templeton A. R.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2013",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ab1dda1e-95c2-4087-8299-e851e58bdc6f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Humans",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1c019e7a-adf5-4cb8-9794-e356d667cac4",
                     "text": "Jablonski, N. G.",
                     "page": "pp. 590, 599 - 615",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<style>.palette{ display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap;justify-content:center; max-width:500px; margin:15px auto; gap:6px; } .color-swatch{ width:28px; height:28px; border-radius:6px; cursor:pointer; border:2px solid transparent; transition:0.2s; } .color-swatch:hover{ transform:scale(1.1); } .color-swatch.active{ border:2px solid #000; } #leftHand{ transform:translateX(-140px); transform-origin:center; } #rightHand{  transform:translateX(140px);  transform-origin:center;} @keyframes clapLeft{ 0%{ transform:translateX(-140px); }  50%{ transform:translateX(0px); } 100%{ transform:translateX(-140px); } } @keyframes clapRight{  0%{ transform:translateX(140px); }  50%{ transform:translateX(0px); } 100%{ transform:translateX(140px); } } .speed-control { margin-top: 15px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; gap: 10px; } .speed-control label { font-size: 16px; } #speedSlider {  width: 200px;   cursor: pointer; }  @keyframes jump { 0% { transform: scale(1); } 50% { transform: scale(1.05); } 100% { transform: scale(1); } } .feet-jumping {  animation: jump var(--jump-duration) ease;   transform-origin: center; } @keyframes simpleZoom { 0% { transform: scale(1); } 50% { transform: scale(1.15); } 100% { transform: scale(1); } } @keyframes leftFootZoom { 0% { transform: scale(-1,1) scale(1); } 50% { transform: scale(-1,1) scale(1.15); } 100% { transform: scale(-1,1) scale(1); } } @keyframes rightFootZoom { 0% { transform: translate(1000px, 0) scale(1,1) scale(1); } 50% { transform: translate(1011px, 0) scale(1,1) scale(1.15); } 100% { transform: translate(1011px, 0) scale(1,1) scale(1); } } .zoom-left { animation: leftFootZoom var(--step-duration) ease; transform-origin: center; transform-box: fill-box; } .zoom-right { animation: rightFootZoom var(--step-duration) ease; transform-origin: center; } .svg-container { display: inline-block; width: 100%; max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 10px; box-sizing: border-box; } svg{ display: block; width: 100%; height: auto; max-height: 70vh; overflow:visible; }</style>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
